data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific assert methods that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count explicitly — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or just check exact count | Shows actual value on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure says `Expected:3 Actual:5` instead of just `Expected:True Actual:False` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` | `Single` already throws if missing, making the null check redundant |

**Other useful tools:**

- **`CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`** — membership check
- **`CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`**
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)`** — same items, any order
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — same items, same order

For richer fluent assertions, consider **FluentAssertions** (`dotnet add package FluentAssertions`):

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
